tus of text and gloss, while interpretive interlinear or marginal prompts capture the dynamic relationships among generations of teachers, students, and readers. The material traces of manuscript usage—from hastily scrawled marginal notes to vivid rubrication—illuminate the shared didactic and communicative practices developed within scholarly communities. By bringing together researchers working on specific cultures and discourses across Eurasia, this volume moves toward a global account of premodern commentary traditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCriticism, Medieval. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBuddhist exegesis.  aByzantine.  aGraeco-Roman.  aOttoman.  aSanskrit.  aSino-Tibetan.  aSunni.1 aAkbari, Suzanne Conklin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBennardo, Lorenza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetancourt, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConklin Akbari, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreschi, Elisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, Amanda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGürbüzel, Aslihan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward Masang, Meghan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Sooyong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Jeannie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeterson, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRao, Ajay, econtributo